1. Reading the data and exploring it

First we read the local data file and check its structure and dimensions. As weve written the file as csv, we dont need to explicitly state the separator and header.

rawdata <- read.csv("Z:/IODS-project/data/learning2014.csv")

First we inspect the structure and dimensions of the data we read from a comma-separated values file in the data directory.

str(rawdata)
## 'data.frame':    166 obs. of  7 variables:
##  $ gender  : Factor w/ 2 levels "F","M": 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 1 2 1 ...
##  $ age     : int  53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42 ...
##  $ attitude: int  37 31 25 35 37 38 35 29 38 21 ...
##  $ deep    : num  3.58 2.92 3.5 3.5 3.67 ...
##  $ surf    : num  2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83 ...
##  $ stra    : num  3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62 ...
##  $ points  : int  25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26 ...
dim(rawdata)
## [1] 166   7

The imported data is a subset of survey data collected from students. Their answers to a set of 32 questions have been categorised to measure their self-evaluated tendency towards deep-, strategic-, and surface learning. Their gender, age, and global attitude towards statistics was also asked. Students who received zero points from the course exam are filtered out for this dataset.

The dataset includes 166 observations in 7 dimensions.

2. Delving deeper into the data and exploring variables

You should be familiar with our source data now. Lets examine the whole dataset as a graphical representation, and we can hopefully see some interesting convergence in our data. We now assume that there exists some correlation between the exam points the student has accrued and the other variables.

p <- ggpairs(rawdata, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))
p

From the graphical representation of the data we can see that that there is a moderate positive correlation between exam points and attitude (\(\mathit{r}=.44\)), while the correlation of other variables with exam points is very weak. (\(\mathit{r} <.2\)) The variables correlate generally quite weakly, the exception being the weak negative correlation between surface learning with deep learning (\(\mathit{r} = -.32\))

Especially interesting is the relationship between age and all the numeric variables, where only very weak correlations can be found. (\(\mathit{r} \le \pm .141\))

Next well take a look at the summaries of the variables.

3. Choosing variables, fitting a regression model and interpreting it

Based on the correlation between the variables, we now select attitude, strategic learning tendency and surface learning tendency as explanatory variables in a linear regression model, where exam points are the dependent variable. We anticipate that the dependent variable shows a statistically significant dependency (\(p < .05\)) to the explanatory variables.

We also print the summary of the model for further analysis.

my_model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = rawdata)
summary(my_model1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = rawdata)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.1550  -3.4346   0.5156   3.6401  10.8952 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 11.01711    3.68375   2.991  0.00322 ** 
## attitude     0.33952    0.05741   5.913 1.93e-08 ***
## stra         0.85313    0.54159   1.575  0.11716    
## surf        -0.58607    0.80138  -0.731  0.46563    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.296 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2074, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1927 
## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

The residuals conform moderately to normal distribution, though there is slightly more deviance towards the lower end of the cases.

The logistic regression coefficients give the change in the logistic odds of the outcome for a one unit increase in the predictor variable. Hence, for each unit increase in attitude the logistic odds of higher exam points increase by ~0.34.

The estimated coefficient of the variable essentially tells us the value of the slope calculated by the regression. The standard error of the coefficient estimate should optimally be at least a magnitude less than the estimated coefficient, and this is true only for attitude.

The probability that each variable would NOT be relevant is displayed as the Pr(>|t|). For attitude, the probability is 0.0000000193, which is statistically significant on the selected threshold (\(p<.05\)). For strategic learning the probability is 0.11716 and for surface learning 0.46563, both of which are over the selected threshold for statistic significance.

Change model by dropping insignificant variables

We now change the model to include only attitude as the sole explanatory variable and print out the summary of the model.

my_model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = rawdata)

4. Analysing the new model

We now print the summary of the renewed model for analysis.

summary(my_model1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = rawdata)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 11.63715    1.83035   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude     0.35255    0.05674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

The higher value of the F-statistic (38.61 > 14.13) implies that the removal of the statistically insignificant variables resulted in better performance of the model with fewer variables.

The Multiple R-square value evaluates the quality of the fit of the model, with higher values indicating a better fit and a value of 1 indicating a perfect fit. The lower R-squared of the new model compared to the model with more variables (0.1906 < 0.2073) implies that the new model would be a worse fit than the previous one. The R-squared in this test implies that ~19% of the exam points are due to the students attitude, but even a good fit does NOT always imply causation

Lastly we diagnose the new model.

5. Diagnostic plots of the model and their analysis

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(my_model1, which = c(1:2, 5))

The basic assumption of the first model - that all of the original three explanatory variables would have a statistically significant connection to the dependent variable - was false.

In the new model, the three outliers (low exam points for students with a highly positive attitude towards statistics) are clearly visible.

The lack of Cooks distance on the residuals v leverage plot shows that there are no overly influential data points in the selected cases, i.e.even the high attitude-low score cases are a passable fit to the model.

From the glimpse() to the data we can see that is comprises 382 observations of 35 variables. The observations of the variables containt the attributes of the students, their socio-economic information and additional background information like the existence of internet access and the quality of their family relationships. The students alcohol usage is measured by daily and weekly consumption on a scale of 1-5, the average of the two, and a binary high consumption variable with an average consumption of over 2 as the limit.

Further information on all of the variables, except for the calulated ones, is available from the source

We now select four interesting variables for further analysis and make a hypothesis for each in relation to their effect on the students alcohol consumption.

Family relationships:
H0: The quality of family relationships has no correlation to high alcohol consumption.
H1: The quality of family relationships has a negative correlation to high alcohol consumption.

Absences:
H0: The amount of absences has no correlation to high alcohol consumption.
H1: The amount of absences has a positive correlation to high alcohol consumption.

Gender:
H0: Gender has no correlation to high alcohol consumption.
H1: Female students are less prone to high alcohol consumption than male students.

Extra-curriculars:
H0: Engaging in extra-curricular activities has no correlation to high alcohol consumption.
H1: Students with extra-curricular activities are less prone to high alcohol consumption than students with no extra-curricular activities.

Task 4

We will proceed with examining the relationships between variables pertinent for each hypothesis to average alcohol consumption.

Family relationships

plot(factor(high_use)~factor(famrel), xlab="Quality of family relationships", ylab="Avg alcohol use", main="Family relationships")

The correlation of the quality of family relationships to alcohol use does not seem large. The prevalence of high alcohol consumption is approximately the same in students with poor quality family relationships (=1) and students with high quality family relationships (=5). The number of students with the poorest quality family relationships appears to be the smallest in the dataset, while a large majority of students have evaluated their family relationships to be in the best two categories (4-5).

Absences

plot(factor(high_use), absences, xlab="High alcohol use", ylab="Number of absences", main="Absences", type = "l")

From the boxplot we can see that students with more absences are more prone to high alcohol use, as the median, upper quartile and maximum (excluding outliers) for low alcohol use stay at just over 10 absences.

Gender

plot(factor(high_use)~factor(sex), xlab="Gender of the student", ylab="High alcohol use", main="Gender")

The data shows that female students consume less alcohol than male students. Furthermore, the proportions of observations from females and males are quite even.

Extra-curriculars

plot(factor(high_use)~factor(activities), xlab="Does the student engage in extracurriculars", ylab="High alcohol consumption", main="Extracurriculars")

Engaging in extracurricular activities does not seem to correlate to a large degree with high alcohol consumption.

Task 6

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
rawdata <- mutate(rawdata, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
rawdata <- mutate(rawdata, prediction = probability > 0.5)
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.3
# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = rawdata$high_use, prediction = rawdata$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   250   18
##    TRUE     84   30

Bonus: 10-fold cross-validation

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = rawdata$high_use, prob = rawdata$probability)
## [1] 0.2670157
# K-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = rawdata, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2696335

Task 3 - PCA

pca_human <- prcomp(human)
biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2, cex = 0.4)

Task 4 - Standardisation and new PCA

human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human_std <- prcomp(human_std)
biplot(pca_human_std, choices = 1:2, cex = 0.4)

The unstandardised plot does not offer substantial information in addition to the large variance in GNI. From the GNI we can deduce that oil-rich countries are leading the pack with Singapore and Luxembourg. The effect of the GNI dominance in the first principal component (PC1) makes the second and subsequence principal components undiscernible.

Standardising the variables make the principal component graph more readable by diminishing the dominance of GNI.

From the standardised biplot we can find three dimensions of interconnected variables: GNI, life expectancy, expected years of schooling and the ratio of females to males with at least secondary education are grouped together; the ratio of females to males in the labour force are grouped together, and maternal mortality rate and adolescent birth rate are grouped together. These groupings correspond to the correlation coefficients analysed earlier.

Task 5 - Interpretations

When analysed through principal component 1, the first grouping is a polar opponent to the third grouping, with both adolescent births and maternal mortality decreasing when GNI, life expectancy, and education levels increase.
